---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Container from "@/components/container.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Evolution: From SV Labs to EduMyna"
  description="A 12-year journey through multiple pivots, experiments, and transformations—from physical incubator to AI-first education platform."
>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-slate-900 via-slate-800 to-slate-900 text-white border-b border-slate-700">
    <Container>
      <div class="max-w-5xl py-24 md:py-32">
        <p class="text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-slate-400 mb-6">12 Years of Evolution</p>
        <h1 class="text-5xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-bold tracking-tight leading-tight mb-6">
          From <span class="text-blue-400">Physical Walls</span> to <span class="text-emerald-400">Digital Scale</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-slate-300 max-w-4xl leading-relaxed">
          The complete story of organizational transformation: SV Labs → Startup Village Collective → Pupilfirst → The Second Design → EduMyna. Five major pivots. Dozens of experiments. One unwavering mission.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-10 flex flex-wrap gap-4">
          <a href="#timeline" class="bg-white text-slate-900 px-6 py-3 rounded-lg font-semibold hover:bg-slate-100 transition">
            View Timeline →
          </a>
          <a href="#business-model" class="border border-white/30 text-white px-6 py-3 rounded-lg font-semibold hover:bg-white/10 transition">
            Business Model Evolution
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </Container>
  </section>

  <Container>
    <article class="max-w-6xl mx-auto py-16 md:py-24">

      <!-- Introduction -->
      <section class="mb-20">
        <div class="max-w-3xl">
          <p class="text-xl text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Most founder stories are linear: "We had an idea, built it, scaled it." This isn't that story.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xl text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            This is a story of <strong>continuous transformation</strong>—of an organization that changed its business model, product, customer base, and delivery mechanism multiple times over twelve years, while keeping the core mission unchanged: <em>enable people to enable themselves through better education</em>.
          </p>
          <p class="text-xl text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            What follows is an honest account of how organizations actually evolve—messy, uncertain, but deeply intentional.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Act 1: Physical Beginning -->
      <section class="mb-24 scroll-mt-24" id="act1">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-8">
          <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-amber-500 to-orange-600 flex items-center justify-center text-white text-2xl font-bold shadow-lg">
            I
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-bold tracking-widest uppercase text-slate-500">Act I &middot; 2012–2015</p>
            <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900">The Physical Beginning</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-600 font-medium">Startup Village: India's First PPP Incubator</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pl-0 md:pl-20 space-y-6">
          <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 p-6 rounded-r-xl">
            <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">The Original Vision</p>
            <p class="text-slate-700">
              Create a "Silicon Coast" in Kerala by building India's first Public-Private-Partnership technology incubator. Physical space. Government backing. Classic startup incubation model.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>What Happened:</strong> In 2012, Startup Village opened its doors in Kochi with 10,000 sq ft of space and ₹2.5 crore in government grants. The model was simple: provide physical infrastructure, mentorship, and capital access to early-stage startups.
          </p>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-8">
            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6 text-center">
              <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">500</div>
              <div class="text-sm text-slate-600 font-medium">Startups Supported</div>
              <div class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-1">(Promised: 48)</div>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6 text-center">
              <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">3,139</div>
              <div class="text-sm text-slate-600 font-medium">Jobs Created</div>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white border-2 border-slate-200 rounded-xl p-6 text-center">
              <div class="text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">₹45Cr</div>
              <div class="text-sm text-slate-600 font-medium">Funding Raised</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>The Breakthrough Insight (March 2015):</strong> "We've built a community, not a platform." The model was entirely dependent on a handful of people showing up every day for every startup. No repeatable systems. No scalable delivery. Great for the lucky few who got attention—insufficient for everyone else.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-slate-100 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-300">
            <p class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">🔑 Key Learning</p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
              <em>"At scale, one person can't help a thousand people."</em> Physical infrastructure doesn't scale. Artisanal mentorship doesn't scale. You need platforms, systems, and automation.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>The Strategic Pivot:</strong> In January 2015, leadership made a critical decision: "Student startups only." Stop trying to serve everyone. Focus exclusively on college students. This constraint forced specificity—what do students <em>actually</em> need? Not general startup advice. Structured learning. Progression. Skills development.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Act 2: Digital Experiment -->
      <section class="mb-24 scroll-mt-24" id="act2">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-8">
          <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-500 to-indigo-600 flex items-center justify-center text-white text-2xl font-bold shadow-lg">
            II
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-bold tracking-widest uppercase text-slate-500">Act II &middot; 2014–2018</p>
            <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900">The Digital Experiment</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-600 font-medium">SV.CO: Web-Only Platform for Student Startups</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pl-0 md:pl-20 space-y-6">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>February 2015:</strong> The announcement. Physical operations would wind down. SV.CO (Startup Village Collective) would become the future—a pure web platform for student startups. No mobile apps. No physical space requirements. Web-first, structured progression, cohort-based delivery.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-6 rounded-r-xl">
            <p class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">The Product Evolution</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
              <li>✓ Timeline feature for every startup's progress</li>
              <li>✓ 5/10/20/30 stage progression models</li>
              <li>✓ Six-week cohort cycles with structured check-ins</li>
              <li>✓ Submission-based advancement (ship to progress)</li>
              <li>✓ Peer feedback and founder community features</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>April 2016:</strong> SV.CO spun off as a private for-profit company. Team moved to Bangalore. Major product decision: removed "Hustlers" (non-technical founders), went "Hackers only." Developer-focused from this point forward.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>June 2017 - The Trip That Changed Everything:</strong> Took a cohort to Silicon Valley—Google, Facebook, structured mentorship. What the founder came back with wasn't enthusiasm. It was <em>clarity about the gap</em>.
          </p>

          <blockquote class="bg-slate-900 text-white rounded-xl p-8 my-8">
            <p class="text-xl italic leading-relaxed mb-4">
              "The Valley wasn't producing great founders because of incubators. It was producing them because the <em>education system</em> was building people who could actually make things."
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">— Realization, Post-Silicon Valley Trip, July 2017</p>
          </blockquote>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>The Question That Unlocked Everything:</strong>
          </p>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
            <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-300 rounded-xl p-6">
              <p class="text-sm font-bold text-red-900 mb-2">❌ Old Question</p>
              <p class="text-red-800">"How do we help students start startups?"</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-500 rounded-xl p-6">
              <p class="text-sm font-bold text-green-900 mb-2">✓ New Question</p>
              <p class="text-green-800">"How do we help students become <strong>genuinely capable</strong>?"</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>November 2017:</strong> "SV.CO Chapter 2" document penned. Complete strategic pivot: <em>skills over startups</em>. Developer skills specifically. Ship real code that runs in production. The startup narrative was officially over.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>December 2017:</strong> Communication to all users: "We've switched to an Internet Product School." The transformation was complete.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Act 3: University Integration -->
      <section class="mb-24 scroll-mt-24" id="act3">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-8">
          <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-500 to-pink-600 flex items-center justify-center text-white text-2xl font-bold shadow-lg">
            III
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-bold tracking-widest uppercase text-slate-500">Act III &middot; 2018–2023</p>
            <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900">University Integration Era</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-600 font-medium">Pupilfirst: Building the LMS, Partnering with Giants</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pl-0 md:pl-20 space-y-6">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>2018: The Year of Experiments</strong> — The team ran multiple simultaneous experiments to find product-market fit:
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-6 py-2">
              <p class="font-bold text-slate-900">Hackkar (April–October 2018)</p>
              <p class="text-slate-700">Developer hiring platform connecting tier 2/3 college students with companies. Learned the limits: timing mismatches (companies need year-round, students graduate once), and big companies have hiring figured out. Shut down after learning.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-6 py-2">
              <p class="font-bold text-slate-900">Apple iOS School @ Manipal (June 2018)</p>
              <p class="text-slate-700">First credit-integrated university program. Students could take the course as an elective. This model <em>worked</em>. It would become the template for future partnerships.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-6 py-2">
              <p class="font-bold text-slate-900">Facebook VR Partnership (August 2018)</p>
              <p class="text-slate-700">Facebook-funded School of Innovation program across multiple batches. Built Coach Dashboard for external faculty. Key learning: <strong>mission alignment matters operationally</strong>. When funders don't own the vision, things drift.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-6 py-2">
              <p class="font-bold text-slate-900">Freshworks @ Sastra University (2018)</p>
              <p class="text-slate-700">SaaS developer program with genuine ownership from Freshworks. They wanted curriculum open-sourced. They wanted students who could actually build. Mission alignment was real—programs worked.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mt-8">
            <strong>December 5, 2018:</strong> pupilfirst.com domain registered.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-purple-50 border-l-4 border-purple-500 p-6 rounded-r-xl my-8">
            <p class="font-semibold text-purple-900 mb-2">The SaaS Realization</p>
            <p class="text-purple-800">
              The platform they'd built—cohort management, submission tracking, feedback loops, progression logic, curriculum system—was comparable to Teachable.com (valued at $100M+). They could separate the brand from the framework and turn it into SaaS.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>2019: Building the Platform</strong>
          </p>

          <ul class="space-y-3 text-slate-700">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-purple-600 font-bold mt-1">→</span>
              <span><strong>January–March:</strong> Built school administration interface. Replaced ActiveAdmin backend. Elevated admin features to first-class (not just backend tools).</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-purple-600 font-bold mt-1">→</span>
              <span><strong>June 27, 2019:</strong> Major milestone. 316 commits merged in a single day. Student dashboard replacement complete. New curriculum interface launched—WordPress Gutenberg / Medium editor style. Admins could create rich, large documents.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-purple-600 font-bold mt-1">→</span>
              <span><strong>Tech Stack:</strong> First large-scale use of ReasonML & ReasonReact in production.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mt-6">
            <strong>2020–2021: The Pandemic Advantage</strong>
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            Online-first wasn't an experiment anymore—it was the only way. Pupilfirst had been building online-first for years. That gave them a structural advantage when the world went remote.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-slate-100 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-300 my-8">
            <p class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-3">🔓 Open Source Commitment</p>
            <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
              Pupilfirst open-sourced the entire platform. Curriculum. Infrastructure. Everything. Not as an upsell—as a principle. Knowledge shouldn't be locked in proprietary systems.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            The team also learned: education isn't just a curriculum problem. It's a <strong>policy problem, teacher incentive problem, stakeholder alignment problem, and delivery problem</strong>—all at once. AICTE conversations. CBSE programs. National-level partnerships. They were trying to understand how to make the system work better for <em>everyone</em>, not just the students who found them.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Act 4: The Great Unbundling -->
      <section class="mb-24 scroll-mt-24" id="act4">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-8">
          <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-emerald-500 to-teal-600 flex items-center justify-center text-white text-2xl font-bold shadow-lg">
            IV
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-bold tracking-widest uppercase text-slate-500">Act IV &middot; 2023–2024</p>
            <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900">The Great Unbundling</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-600 font-medium">Direct-to-Consumer + Academic Bank of Credits</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pl-0 md:pl-20 space-y-6">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>November 2023: "LITE is a failure—stop it."</strong>
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            The Pupilfirst Status Update document was brutally honest. The B2B2C university-integrated model (called "LITE") wasn't working at scale. Universities moved slowly. Integration was complex. The vision—reach millions of students—required a different approach.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-emerald-50 border-l-4 border-emerald-500 p-6 rounded-r-xl">
            <p class="font-semibold text-emerald-900 mb-2">The New Strategy: Direct-to-Consumer + Credits</p>
            <p class="text-emerald-800 mb-4">
              Sell directly to students. Offer industry-recognized credentials <em>plus</em> government-backed Academic Bank of Credits (ABC). Integration with India's National Credit Framework (NCrF). Students could stack micro-credentials into degrees.
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-emerald-700 italic">
              Pricing: ₹999/month or ₹4,999/6 months. Frictionless signup. No university gatekeepers.
            </p>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>The Philosophical Shift:</strong> Instead of trying to fix universities from within (B2B2C), go around them (B2C) while simultaneously offering a path <em>back into</em> the formal system via transferable credits. Unbundle traditional degrees, then offer a pathway to re-bundle them—but on the student's terms.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>What Stayed the Same:</strong> The platform. The pedagogy. The commitment to open-source. The focus on <em>actually teaching skills</em>, not just issuing certificates.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>What Changed:</strong> Business model (B2B2C → B2C). Customer acquisition (university sales → direct marketing). Pricing (enterprise deals → subscription). Speed of iteration (slow → fast).
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Act 5: AI Revolution -->
      <section class="mb-24 scroll-mt-24" id="act5">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mb-8">
          <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-rose-500 to-red-600 flex items-center justify-center text-white text-2xl font-bold shadow-lg">
            V
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-sm font-bold tracking-widest uppercase text-slate-500">Act V &middot; 2024–Present</p>
            <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900">The AI Revolution</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-600 font-medium">Automation-First, Intelligence-Augmented Learning</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pl-0 md:pl-20 space-y-6">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>The Final Constraint:</strong> To reach millions of students at ₹999/month, human-intensive operations don't work. Manual review doesn't scale. Traditional tutoring doesn't scale. You need <em>intelligent automation at every layer</em>.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-rose-50 border-l-4 border-rose-500 p-6 rounded-r-xl">
            <p class="font-semibold text-rose-900 mb-3">AI-First Strategy (2024)</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-rose-800">
              <li>✓ <strong>Automated grading and feedback</strong> using LLMs trained on expert review patterns</li>
              <li>✓ <strong>Personalized learning paths</strong> adapting to student progress and gaps</li>
              <li>✓ <strong>AI teaching assistants</strong> providing 24/7 support in student's language</li>
              <li>✓ <strong>Content generation at scale</strong>—curriculum variants, practice problems, examples</li>
              <li>✓ <strong>Predictive intervention</strong>—identifying struggling students before they drop out</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>The Human Role Evolved:</strong> Instead of teachers spending time on repetitive tasks (grading, answering common questions, generating practice problems), they focus on high-value interactions: designing curriculum, mentoring complex problems, building relationships, inspiring students.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>The Economic Model Works:</strong> At ₹999/month with AI-driven delivery, unit economics become sustainable at scale. Traditional ed-tech required either high prices (₹50K–₹2L courses) or massive scale with thin margins (freemium models). AI enables high-quality delivery at mid-tier pricing.
          </p>

          <blockquote class="bg-slate-900 text-white rounded-xl p-8 my-8">
            <p class="text-xl italic leading-relaxed">
              "We've spent twelve years learning what students need. Now we have the technology to deliver it to millions—without sacrificing quality for scale."
            </p>
          </blockquote>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            <strong>EduMyna Emerges (2024):</strong> The integration of all learnings. Infrastructure from Pupilfirst. Pedagogy from The Second Design (RealWorldReady programs). AI-first delivery. Direct-to-consumer reach. Credit integration. Open-source commitment.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-slate-900 to-slate-800 text-white rounded-2xl p-8 my-8">
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">EduMyna's Mission</h3>
            <p class="text-slate-200 leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Enable <strong>millions of students</strong> to gain industry-relevant skills, earn recognized credentials, and build agency—through high-quality, affordable, AI-augmented education delivered on open-source infrastructure.
            </p>
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 italic">
              Same mission as 2009. Completely different delivery mechanism.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Timeline Visualization -->
      <section class="mb-24 scroll-mt-24" id="timeline">
        <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-12 text-center">Visual Timeline: 12 Years of Evolution</h2>

        <div class="relative">
          <!-- Timeline line -->
          <div class="absolute left-8 top-0 bottom-0 w-1 bg-gradient-to-b from-amber-500 via-blue-500 via-purple-500 via-emerald-500 to-rose-500"></div>

          <!-- Timeline items -->
          <div class="space-y-12 relative pl-20">

            <!-- 2012-2015 -->
            <div class="relative">
              <div class="absolute -left-12 top-0 w-16 h-16 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-amber-500 to-orange-600 flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold shadow-xl border-4 border-white">
                2012
              </div>
              <div class="bg-white border-2 border-amber-200 rounded-xl p-6 hover:shadow-lg transition">
                <p class="text-sm font-bold text-amber-600 mb-1">Physical Beginning</p>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Startup Village, Kochi</h3>
                <p class="text-slate-700 mb-3">India's first PPP incubator. 500 startups supported. ₹45Cr funding raised. Community-driven, founder-dependent.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600"><strong>Business Model:</strong> Government grants + CSR funding</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600"><strong>Delivery:</strong> Physical incubator, in-person mentorship</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 2014-2015 -->
            <div class="relative">
              <div class="absolute -left-12 top-0 w-16 h-16 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-500 to-indigo-600 flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold shadow-xl border-4 border-white">
                2015
              </div>
              <div class="bg-white border-2 border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-6 hover:shadow-lg transition">
                <p class="text-sm font-bold text-blue-600 mb-1">Digital Transformation</p>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">SV.CO Platform Launched</h3>
                <p class="text-slate-700 mb-3">Web-only platform. Student startups only. Structured cohorts. Progression models. Beginning of scalable delivery.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600"><strong>Business Model:</strong> Freemium + cohort fees</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600"><strong>Delivery:</strong> Pure web, asynchronous + live sessions</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 2017 -->
            <div class="relative">
              <div class="absolute -left-12 top-0 w-16 h-16 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-indigo-500 to-purple-600 flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold shadow-xl border-4 border-white">
                2017
              </div>
              <div class="bg-white border-2 border-indigo-200 rounded-xl p-6 hover:shadow-lg transition">
                <p class="text-sm font-bold text-indigo-600 mb-1">Strategic Pivot</p>
                <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Skills Over Startups</h3>
                <p class="text-slate-700 mb-3">Post-Silicon Valley trip realization. Complete departure from startup narrative. Focus: developer skills, ship real code.</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600"><strong>Customer:</strong> Students wanting skills (not startup founders)</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-slate-600"><strong>Value Prop:</strong> "Become genuinely capable"</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 2018 -->
            <div class="relative">
              <div class="absolute -left-12 top-0 w-16 h-16 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-500 to-pink-600 flex items-center justify-center text-white font-bold shadow-xl border-4 border-white">
                2018
              </div>
              <div class="bg-white border-2 border-purple-200 rounded-xl p-6 hover:shadow-lg transition">
